The United States economy added 223,000 jobs in May, exceeding expectations. The unemployment rate also matched its lowest level in almost five decades at 3.8 percent. Additionally, small companies in the US are raising wages at a record high, and optimism about the availability of quality jobs has reached its highest level in 17 years. Job openings in March hit an all-time high of 6.6 million, and consumer confidence remains close to an 18-year high. Furthermore, consumer spending increased by 0.6 percent in April, the largest increase in five months. US households and businesses are feeling more stable and optimistic, according to surveys conducted by the Federal Reserve. The US has also regained its position as the world's most competitive economy. As a result of tax cuts, US companies are expected to invest more in business this year. Finally, US manufacturing activity is at its strongest level since September 2014.